1 enhancement efforts of the state agencies; and
2
3 WHEREAS, the Sport Fish Restoration Program, which began seventy-five
4 (75) years ago with the passage of the Federal Aid in Sport Fish Restoration
5 Act in 1950 is a vital part of conservation funding in the United States; and
6
7 WHEREAS, the Federal Aid in Sport Fish Restoration Act was further
8 expanded with the Wallop-Breaux amendment in 1984; and
9
10 WHEREAS, a manufacturers excise tax on fishing equipment, along with an
11 excise tax on motorboat and small engine fuels, is mostly distributed back to
12 the states through the United States Fish and Wildlife Service for fisheries
13 conservation, management, and angler and boater access; and
14
15 WHEREAS, this cooperative partnership between the sportfishing
16 industry, anglers, boaters, the United States Fish and Wildlife Service, and
17 state natural resource agencies has resulted in the most successful model of
18 fisheries management in the world, restoring and enhancing populations across
19 the United States and its territories; and
20
21 WHEREAS, since 1939, the combined contribution of the Wildlife and
22 Sport Fish Restoration Program, and license fees to state fish and wildlife
23 agencies exceeds seventy-eight billion dollars ($78,000,000,000) and this is
24 more than any other single conservation effort in American history,
25
26 NOW THEREFORE,
27 BE IT RESOLVED BY THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES OF THE NINETY-FIFTH GENERAL
28 ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF ARKANSAS:
29
30 THAT the House of Representatives recognize America’s anglers, boaters,
31 the sportfishing industry, state fish and wildlife agencies, and the United
32 States Fish and Wildlife Service for their leading role in restoring healthy
33 populations of fish and aquatic resources, both game and nongame, to the
34 abundance we see today with the help of the Sport Fish Restoration Program,
35 in this the seventy-fifth (75th) anniversary year of the program’s
36 establishment as part of the American System of Conservation Funding.
